 nowrap><b><font color="#000000" face="arial" size="2">Rigorre Morrtisse</font></b></td>
                <td bgcolor="#e9e9e9" valign="top"><font color="#000000" face="arial" size="2"><small>Posted&nbsp;-&nbsp;06/18/2003&nbsp;: 08:44:32 AM</small><hr size="2"><span class="spnMessageText"> <blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">2) bugged like hell, no way it will go live when planned<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote">You live in your own world.  It will go live on the day they say it will ...bugged and all.  Why?  Because it is about money ...stockholders, overhead, profit margins ...absolutely nothing having to do with whether or not it is a 'good' game with as few bugs as possible.<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">For EQ2, it will really be very different, the project has almost no common scheme with SWG. SWG must adapt to an universe clearly detailed, dev team must respect many many many things...in EQ2, the story isn't already written, things can be very different.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote">What technical aspects of EQ2 are already available, it is easy to see that they intend to pattern EQ2 after SWG.  Obviously, the story lines are different ...but the technical aspects of the games could be very very similar.  Lets look at a few of the published 'features' and compare:<br /><br />1) ...16 races and 48 classes<br /><b>Only way you could get that many 'classes' is to implement the same system used currently in SWG.  Start with 4 or 5 basic 'classes', use skill trees to 'customize'.</b><br /><br />2) Unparalleled character customization capabilities. In addition to the thousands of armor, weapons and items users will be able to equip, players will be able to customize their face, age, skin tone, eye and hair color<br /><b>Done in SWG.  One of the best parts about SWG is it's player appearance customization.</b><br /><br />3) ...encounter hundreds of creatures as they travel across the majestic landscape of rolling hills, barren deserts, dense forests, and bustling cities.<br /><b>Read the section entitled 'immersiveness' above.</b><br /><br />4) Player-owned real estate (such as apartments, homes, and guild houses)<br /><b>Done, got it in SWG</b><br /><br />5) Player-controlled ships<br /><b>Promised in SWG with a 'space flight' expansion.  Wouldn't look for this one in EQ2 right off the bat.</b><br /><br />6) Dedicated trade skill player class<br /><b>Done, the Artisan starting profession in SWG.</b><br /><br />7) State-of-the-art combat, spell and skill systems  both mechanically and visually<br /><b>Don't even get me started.  SWG combat SUCKS, and just knowing that they are changing combat in EQ2 gives me cause to believe they will screw it up.</b><br /><br />8) Unrivaled quest system<br /><b>Read the 'missions' section above.</b><br /><br /></span></font></td>
